---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Zheng et al. (2026) — Binary disruption in early open clusters";
import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Zheng et al. (2026) — Binary disruption during the early phase of open clusters</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Paper</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Paper</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Authors:</th><td>Zepeng Zheng, Long Wang, Holger Baumgardt</td></tr>
        <tr><th>arXiv:</th><td><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11803">2603.11803</a></td></tr>
        <tr><th>Accepted:</th><td>ApJ (accepted)</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Abstract (short)</strong> — N-body simulations based on Gaia DR3 clusters show binary disruption has two stages (rapid then slow). The early disruption rate scales with initial density and depends on binary parameters; a public Python tool is released for predicting survival fractions.</p>

    <h2>Key claims</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Two-stage binary disruption: rapid initial loss then slower decline.</li>
      <li>Early disruption rate k1 ∝ ρ0^0.56; transition time tb ∝ ρ0^-0.46.</li>
      <li>High-q and wide binaries are disrupted faster; escaped stars form a lower-binary-fraction field population.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>See also</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/open_cluster_binary_disruption" text="Open cluster binary disruption" /></li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/mass_segregation" text="Mass segregation" /></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Zheng et al. (2026). <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11803">arXiv:2603.11803</a>.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
